Wash and dry all produce. Preheat the #oven{} to 400 degrees (or fire up the #grill{} to high!). Finely chop the @parsley{1/4%ounce}. Zest, then halve the @lemon{1}. Mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Slice the @roma tomato{1} into rounds.

In a #large bowl{}, combine the @coleslaw mix{5%ounce}, half the parsley, @mayonnaise{1%tablespoon}, @sugar{1/4%teaspoon}, and a squeeze of lemon juice. Season generously with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> Cubed avocado lends this side slaw a little extra creaminess.

In a #small bowl{}, combine the remaining parsley, a pinch of lemon zest, a pinch of garlic (to taste), a squeeze of lemon juice, and a drizzle of @olive oil{2%teaspoon}. Season with salt and pepper. Taste and adjust with more salt, lemon, oil, or garlic, as needed.

Cook the burgers: Form the @ground beef{10%ounce} into 2 patties roughly the size of the buns. Season generously on both sides with salt and pepper.

> TIP: If you have a grill, you can cook the burgers and toast the buns there instead!

If not, heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add the burgers to the pan and cook for ~{2-4%minutes} per side, or until cooked to desired doneness. After you flip the burgers, top with the @Monterey Jack cheese{1/2%cup} and cover the pan to melt.

While the burgers cook, split the @brioche buns{2} and place in the oven to toast for about ~{5%minutes}. Halve, pit, and thinly slice half the @avocado{1}. Cube the remaining avocado and mix into the slaw.

Assemble the burgers and serve: Fill each bun with a burger, a generous spoonful of chimichurri, avocado slices, and tomato slices. If you like, spread the top bun with any remaining mayonnaise. Serve the cabbage slaw to the side and enjoy!